1 WHEREAS, proposed legislation to establish a statewide livable wage beginning at
2 $10.25 per hour with future adjustments tied to inflation has failed; and
3 WHEREAS, despite the rising cost of basic necessities, many Louisiana workers
4 continue to earn wages so low that they are unable to secure stable housing, reliable
5 transportation, nutritious food, health care, childcare, or educational opportunity for
6 themselves and their families; and
7 WHEREAS, a full-time worker earning the federal minimum wage earns
8 approximately $15,080 annually before taxes, an amount that falls far below what the
9 Massachusetts Institute of Technology Living Wage Calculator opines is necessary to
10 maintain even a modest standard of living; and
11 WHEREAS, low wages force many working families into impossible choices
12 between rent and medicine, groceries and utilities, and transportation and childcare, thereby
13 perpetuating cycles of poverty, housing insecurity, debt, and economic instability; and
14 WHEREAS, the continued existence of poverty wages disproportionately harms
15 women, immigrant communities, disabled individuals, rural residents, and other historically
16 marginalized populations throughout Louisiana; and
17 WHEREAS, workers who perform essential labor deserve compensation that reflects
18 the value, dignity, and necessity of their work, particularly after the sacrifices made by
19 frontline workers during public health emergencies, natural disasters, and economic crises;
20 and
21 WHEREAS, paying workers a livable wage strengthens local economies by
22 increasing consumer spending, reducing employee turnover, improving workplace morale,
23 stimulating small business growth, and decreasing dependence on publicly funded assistance
24 programs; and
25 WHEREAS, numerous economists, labor advocates, faith leaders, and public policy
26 organizations have concluded that raising wages contributes to improved health outcomes,
27 educational attainment, community stability, and long-term economic growth; and
28 WHEREAS, Louisiana consistently ranks among the poorest states in the nation in
29 measures of poverty, health outcomes, educational opportunity, and economic mobility,
30 conditions that are heightened by persistently low wages; and
